{"query": {"pages": {"11296342": {"lastrevid": 635841517, "pageid": 11296342, "canonicalurl": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chandrakala_A._Hate", "title": "Chandrakala A. Hate", "editurl": "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Chandrakala_A._Hate&action=edit", "length": 3219, "contentmodel": "wikitext", "pagelanguage": "en", "touched": "2015-03-30T12:13:44Z", "ns": 0, "fullurl": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chandrakala_A._Hate", "revisions": [{"*": "<p><b>Dr. Chandrakala Anandrao Hate, M.A., Ph.D.</b> (1903\u20131990) (<a href=\"/wiki/N%C3%A9e\" title=\"N\u00e9e\" class=\"mw-redirect\">n\u00e9e</a> Murkute) was a prominent author, <a href=\"/wiki/Feminist\" title=\"Feminist\" class=\"mw-redirect\">feminist</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Social_worker\" title=\"Social worker\" class=\"mw-redirect\">social worker</a>, and professor in <a href=\"/wiki/Bombay\" title=\"Bombay\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Bombay</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/India\" title=\"India\">India</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><div id=\"toctitle\"><h2>Contents</h2></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Biography\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Biography</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Early_years\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Early years</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Career\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Career</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Personal\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Personal</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Biography\">Biography</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Chandrakala_A._Hate&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Biography\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Early_years\">Early years</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Chandrakala_A._Hate&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Early years\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Born Chandrakala Jagannath Murkute on 12 September 1903 to Dr. Jagannath and Lahanibai Murkute, she was born into a family belonging to <a href=\"/wiki/Mumbai\" title=\"Mumbai\">Mumbai</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/Daivadnya\" title=\"Daivadnya\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Daivadnya</a> community. Education played an important role from early on in her life. She went on to marry Anandrao Ramkrishna Hate (pronounced Haa-tay).\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Career\">Career</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Chandrakala_A._Hate&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Career\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Much of Dr. Hate's work entailed studying and improving the status of women in Indian society. She received an <a href=\"/wiki/Master_of_Arts_(postgraduate)\" title=\"Master of Arts (postgraduate)\" class=\"mw-redirect\">M.A.</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Economics\" title=\"Economics\">Economics</a> and wrote <i>Hindu Woman and Her Future</i> (1948) for her <a href=\"/wiki/Ph.D.\" title=\"Ph.D.\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Ph.D.</a> thesis in <a href=\"/wiki/Sociology\" title=\"Sociology\">Sociology</a>, advised by the influential <a href=\"/wiki/Sociologist\" title=\"Sociologist\" class=\"mw-redirect\">sociologist</a> Dr. <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=G.S._Ghurye&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"G.S. Ghurye (page does not exist)\">G.S. Ghurye</a>. Considered extremely forward-thinking at that time, the study advocated education of women as well increasing the acceptability of women in the work force.\n</p><p>Continuing to write prolifically, she wrote the books <i>Changing status of woman in post-independence India</i> (1969) and <i>Turn..? whither...? to....?</i> (1978), and contributed often to the many English and <a href=\"/wiki/Marathi_language\" title=\"Marathi language\">Marathi</a> Bombay magazines. Dr. Hate taught as a professor of Sociology at <a href=\"/wiki/SNDT_Women%27s_University\" title=\"SNDT Women's University\">SNDT Women's University</a>, Bombay, and began the organization <i>Kutumb Sakhi</i> in 1975 to help socially disadvantaged women employ themselves.\n</p><p><i>Kutumb Sakhi</i> initially began as a group of women stitching petticoats from cloth purchased from a mill owned by the <a href=\"/wiki/Cricketer\" title=\"Cricketer\" class=\"mw-redirect\">cricketer</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Vijay_Merchant\" title=\"Vijay Merchant\">Vijay Merchant</a>. However, to improve revenue, the organization turned to cooking snack foods; over the years, the organization has become quite successful in the Mumbai eatery business, and in turn, has served a role in empowering many women take control of the own futures. As of 2005, the organization employed around 150 women, many of who are <a href=\"/wiki/Widows\" title=\"Widows\" class=\"mw-redirect\">widows</a> or deserted wives.\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Personal\">Personal</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Chandrakala_A._Hate&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Personal\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Dr. Hate's husband died early in her life, and she raised three sons on her own, playing an important role in the way she viewed much of society. Much of her spiritual support came from the teachings of Gurudev R D Ranade. Dr. Hate died of <a href=\"/wiki/Esophageal_cancer\" title=\"Esophageal cancer\">esophageal cancer</a> in Mumbai in 1990. In the years after, the city of Mumbai dedicated and renamed a <a href=\"//en.wiktionary.org/wiki/chowk\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wikt:chowk\">chowk</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Girgaum\" title=\"Girgaum\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Girgaum</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/South_Mumbai\" title=\"South Mumbai\">South Mumbai</a>, Chandrakalabai Hate Chowk in her honor.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Chandrakala_A._Hate&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li> <span class=\"citation book\">Pillai, S. Devadas (1997). <i>Indian Sociology Through Ghurye: A Dictionary</i>. Popular Prakashan. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/81-7154-807-5\" title=\"Special:BookSources/81-7154-807-5\">81-7154-807-5</a>.</span><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AChandrakala+A.+Hate&amp;rft.aufirst=S.+Devadas&amp;rft.aulast=Pillai&amp;rft.au=Pillai%2C+S.+Devadas&amp;rft.btitle=Indian+Sociology+Through+Ghurye%3A+A+Dictionary&amp;rft.date=1997&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=81-7154-807-5&amp;rft.pub=Popular+Prakashan&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li> \"Feeding Mumbaikars, these women weave their own lives!...\" <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.collegeblews.com/node/3073\">http://www.collegeblews.com/node/3073</a>. Accessed on 10/31/07.</li></ul>\n<table class=\"navbox\" style=\"border-spacing:0\"><tr><td style=\"padding:2px\"><table class=\"nowraplinks